e|CET]]\n| timezone_DST      = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset        = +1\n| utc_offset_DST    = +2\n| registration_plate = [[Vehicle registration plates of Austria|JO]]\n| postal_code_type   = [[List of postal codes in Austria|Postal code]]\n| postal_code        = 5621\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in Austria|Area code]]\n| area_code      = 06415\n| website   = [http://www.gde-stveit.salzburg.at/ www.gde-stveit.salzburg.at]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Sankt Veit im Pongau''' is a market town in the [[St. Johann im Pongau (district)|St. Johann im Pongau district]] in the [[Austria]]n state of [[Salzburg (state)|Salzburg]]. St.Veit is the first healthy climate spa town in Salzburg. Submontane to the \"Hochglocker\" there is the 1912 founded [[sanatorium]]. Author [[Thomas Bernhard]] was treated in there and he also wrote a book about his residence at the clinic.\n\n==Geography==\nThe municipality lies in the [[Pongau]] on the [[Salzach]]. Until Sankt Veit, the Salzach flows from west to east; after Sankt Veit, it flow north. The municipality lies on a high plateau. The climate is tempered by winds that come from the valleys to the south.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in St. Johann im Pongau (district)}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in St. Johann im Pongau District]]\n\n\n{{Salzburg-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n| name            = Sankt Veit im Pongau\n| native_name     = \n| settlement_type = \n<!-- Images     -->\n| image_skyline   = \n| imagesize       = \n| image_caption   = \n| image_shield    = Wappen at st veit.png\n| shield_size     = 80x110px\n| shield_link     = \n<!-- Maps           -->\n| pushpin_map         = Austria\n| pushpin_mapsize     = 270\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within Austria\n| image_map           = \n| mapsize             = \n| map_alt             =\n| map_caption         = Location within St. Johann im Pongau district\n<!-- Location    -->\n| coordinates       = {{coord|47|19|50|N|13|9|20|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type  = Country\n| subdivision_name  = [[Austria]]\n| subdivision_type1 = [[States of Austria|State]]\n| subdivision_name1 = [[Salzburg (state)|Salzburg]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[District (Austria)|District]]\n| subdivision_name2 = [[St. Johann im Pongau District|St. Johann im Pongau]]\n| parts_type        = \n| parts_style       = para\n| p1                = \n<!-- Leaders -->\n| leader_title  = [[Burgomaster|Mayor]]\n| leader_name   = Sebastian Pirnbacher\n| leader_party  = {{Polparty|Austria| [[\u00d6sterreichische Volkspartei|\u00d6VP]] }}\n| leader_title1 = \n| leader_name1  = \n<!-- Statistics -->\n| area_footnotes   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_footnotes}}\n| area_total_km2   = {{Austria population Wikidata|area_total_km2}}\n| area_metro_km2   = \n| elevation_m      = 764\n| elevation_max_m  = \n| elevation_min_m  = \n| population_as_of = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_footnotes}}\n| population_total = {{Austria population Wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_urban =  \n| population_metro =  \n| population_note  = \n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| established_title = \n| established_date  = \n| timezone          = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n| timezone_DST      = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n| utc_offset        = +1\n| utc_offset_DST    = +2\n| registration_plate = [[Vehicle registration plates of Austria|JO]]\n| postal_code_type   = [[List of postal codes in Austria|Postal code]]\n| postal_code        = 5621\n| area_code_type = [[Telephone numbers in Austria|Area code]]\n| area_code      = 06415\n| website   = [http://www.gde-stveit.salzburg.at/ www.gde-stveit.salzburg.at]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Sankt Veit im Pongau''' is a market town in the [[St. Johann im Pongau (district)|St. Johann im Pongau district]] in the [[Austria]]n state of [[Salzburg (state)|Salzburg]]. St.Veit is the first healthy climate spa town in Salzburg. Submontane to the \"Hochglocker\" there is the 1912 founded [[sanatorium]]. Author [[Thomas Bernhard]] was treated in there and he also wrote a book about his residence at the clinic.\n\n==Geography==\nThe municipality lies in the [[Pongau]] on the [[Salzach]]. Until Sankt Veit, the Salzach flows from west to east; after Sankt Veit, it flow north. The municipality lies on a high plateau. The climate is tempered by winds that come from the valleys to the south.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Cities and towns in St. Johann im Pongau (district)}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in St. Johann im Pongau District]]\n\n{{Salzburg-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sankt_Veit_im_Pongau"}
{"title_page": "Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2007}}\n{{short description|educator and founding president of Soka Gakkai}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox President\n|name=Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi\n|image=Makiguchi.jpg\n|office=1st President of [[Soka Gakkai|S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai]]\n|term=18 November 1930 - 18 November 1944\n|successor=[[J\u014dsei Toda]] (removed Ky\u014diku from the organization's name)\n|birth_date=23 July 1871 ([[Lunar calendar]] date on 6 June)\n|birth_place=[[Kashiwazaki, Niigata|Kashiwazaki]], [[Niigata Prefecture]], [[Japan]]\n|death_date=18 November 1944 (aged 73)\n|death_place=[[Sugamo Prison]] (present-day Toda Memorial Auditorium{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}), [[Toshima, Tokyo|Toshima]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|resting_place = [[Taiseki-ji]] Head Temple by Gojunoto Pagoda (left backside), [[Fujinomiya]], [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], Japan<br />{{small|(since 1944\u2013Present)}}\n|alma_mater     = {{plainlist|\n*Sapporo Normal School (present-day [[Hokkaido University of Education]])}}\n}}\n\n{{Buddhism}}\n\n'''Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi''' (\u7267\u53e3 \u5e38\u4e09\u90ce, ''Makiguchi Tsunesabur\u014d'' 23 July 1871<ref>{{cite book|last=Makiguchi|first=Tsunesabur\u014d|date=1989|title=Education for Creative Living|trans-title=Ideas and Proposals of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Education_for_Creative_Living.html?id=AUY4AAAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|language=English|location=Iowa, U.S.|publisher=Iowa State University Press|isbn=0813803918}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.verypdf.com/u/71844/api/20150918-030325-5850041233.pdf|title=Significant SGI Dates|work=VeryPDF Software|publisher=VeryPDF Software}}</ref> [Lunar calendar date on 6 June] \u2013 18 November 1944) was a Japanese educator who founded and became the first president of the S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai (Value-Creating Education Society), the predecessor of today's [[Soka Gakkai]].\n\n== Early life and career ==\nMakiguchi was born in the small village of [[Kashiwazaki, Niigata]] Prefecture, Japan, in 23 July 1871 (Lunar calendar date on 6 June). Adopted by the Makiguchi family, he moved to [[Hokkaido]], Japan's northernmost island, at the age of 14. Working his way through school, he graduated from [[Sapporo]] Normal School (today's [[Hokkaido University of Education]]). First employed as an assistant teacher at a primary school affiliated with his alma mater, he later taught high school and served as a dormitory superintendent.\n\nMakiguchi's environmentally-minded new approach to geography appears in his book ''Jinsei Chirigaku'' (A Geography of Human Life) published in 1903 when he was 32. In this work, Makiguchi rejects the prevailing approach to the study of geography, based on the rote memorization of facts and place names, instead advocating a rational understanding of geography based on the relationship of the individual, human activity and industrial advancement to nature. This is one of, if not the, first published example of modern environmentalist thinking.<ref name=Odata1994>{{cite journal |last=Odata |first=Toshihiro |date=1994 |title=\u7267\u53e3\u5e38\u4e09\u90ce \u300e\u4eba\u751f\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u300f \u306e\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u53f2\u4e0a\u306e\u518d\u8a55\u4fa1 |trans-title=A Reappraisal of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi's 'Jinsei Chirigaku' in the History of Geography in Japan |language=Japanese |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_pdf/-char/en |format=pdf |journal=Chiri-Kagaku [Geographical Sciences] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=197\u2013212 |doi=10.20630/chirikagaku.49.4_197 |accessdate=21 August 2018 |layurl=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_article}}</ref>\n\nAlthough recognized as an able teacher, Makiguchi's uncompromising attitude toward authorities created problems. His clashes with officials of the Ministry of Education, school inspectors, ward assemblymen, city councilmen, and top officials of the city of Tokyo were frequent and resulted in frequent transfers between schools.<ref>Murata, Kiyoaki. ''Japan's New Buddhism: An Objective Account of Soka Gakkai.'' New York and Tokyo: Weatherhill, 1969. pp. 73-74</ref> After moving to Tokyo, he served as principal in a succession of six primary schools, from 1913 to 1932.\n\nDuring those years, he devoted much consideration to the relationship between life and education, developing his theories on ''s\u014dka'' or the creation of value, the happiness of the individual, the prosperity of society at large, and their interrelationships in practice.\n\n== Educational reformer ==\nHis aforementioned work ''Jinsei Chirigaku'' (''A Geography of Human Life''), predates the academic study of geography at the [[Imperial Universities]] of Kyoto and Tokyo in 1907 and 1911, respectively, and pioneered a new approach to teaching geography in Japan. Written between the [[First Sino-Japanese War]] and the [[Russo-Japanese War]], the work presents [[human geography]] as a subject for both [[formal learning|formal]] and [[nonformal learning]] to advance an understanding of cultural differences shaping and shaped by the relationship between human activity and its natural environment.<ref name=Odata1994>{{cite journal |last=Odata |first=Toshihiro |date=1994 |title=\u7267\u53e3\u5e38\u4e09\u90ce \u300e\u4eba\u751f\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u300f \u306e\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u53f2\u4e0a\u306e\u518d\u8a55\u4fa1 |trans-title=A Reappraisal of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi's 'Jinsei Chirigaku' in the History of Geography in Japan |language=Japanese |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_pdf/-char/en |format=pdf |journal=Chiri-Kagaku [Geographical Sciences] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=197\u2013212 |doi=10.20630/chirikagaku.49.4_197 |accessdate=21 August 2018 |layurl=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_article}}</ref> While \"Japanese geographers of the time were chiefly concerned with describing the physical features of the earth,\"<ref>Murata, p72</ref> Makiguchi was arguably the first to discuss human geography as a system of knowledge correlating [[location theory]] and [[spatial distribution]] of human phenomena with economic, social and political geographies.<ref name=Takeuchi-Nozawa1988>{{cite journal |last1=Takeuchi |first1=Keiichi |last2=Nozawa |first2=Hideki |title= Recent Trends in Studies on the History of Geographical Thought in Japan\u2014Mainly on the History of Japanese Geographical Thought |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/grj1984b/61/1/61_1_59/_pdf/-char/en |format=pdf |journal= Geographical Review of Japan |volume=61 (Ser. B) |number=1 |pages=59\u201373 |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>{{rp|64\u201365}} In Makiguchi's words, \"it is through our spiritual interaction with the earth that the characteristics that we think of as human are ignited and nurtured within us.\"<ref>Makiguchi, Tsunesaburo. A Geography of Human Life. Ed. by Dayle M. Bethel. Caddo Gap Press, 2002, p25</ref> In this work, Makiguchi also formulated the concept of humanitarian competition as an approach to international relations, writing that: \"The important thing is the setting of a goal of well being and protection of all people, including oneself but not at the increase of self-interest alone. In other words, the aim is the betterment of others and in doing so, one chooses ways that will yield personal benefit as well as benefits to others. It is a conscious effort to create a more harmonious community life.\"<ref>Makiguchi. A Geography of Human Life. p.286</ref> This publication is one of, if not the, earliest set of ideas in the global modern environmental movement.\n\nIn response to problems throughout the education system that resulted from the Meiji government's adoption of the [[Imperial Rescript]], Makiguchi published the first volume of ''S\u014dka Ky\u014dikugaku Taikei'' (''The System of Value-Creation Pedagogy'') together with his close friend and disciple [[J\u014dsei Toda]] on November 18, 1930.<ref>Kumagaki, Kazunori. \"Value-Creating Pedagogy and Japanese Education in the Modern Era,\" ''The Journal of Oriental Studies, vol. 10 (2000) Special Issue'', p31</ref> The date was later adopted as the Founding Day of S\u014dka Gakkai. The four-volume work, published over a period of five years, sets forth his thoughts on education and proposals for systemic reform. Rather than education serving the state, as embodied in the [[Imperial Rescript on Education]], Makiguchi proposed a student-centered education with the purpose of ensuring the happiness of the learner.<ref>Kumagai, pp32-34</ref>\n\nHe also proposed the creation of an educational system comprising a partnership of school, home and community. In this system, a child would spend half a day in school and the other half in apprenticeships and other types of work activities at home and in the community befitting the nature and needs of the child. Makiguchi felt that implementing such a system would change bored, apathetic learners into eager, self-directed students.\n\n\"Makiguchi developed a theory of value that combined the idea of happiness as the goal of life with that of value as something that can be created. ... In value-creating pedagogy the main point of education is to aim for a happy life and develop the ability and attitude required to create value.\"<ref>Kumagai, p41</ref>\n\n== Conversion to Buddhism==\nIn June 1928, Makiguchi embraced [[Nichiren Buddhism]], having been introduced to Buddhism by his friend Sokei Mitani who was at time working as a [[Meijiro Kenshin Junior and Senior High School|Meijiro high school]] principal in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]]. In Nichiren Buddhism, Makiguchi discovered a deep resonance with ideas he had been developing throughout his life.<ref>https://www.tmakiguchi.org/biography.html</ref>\n\nMakiguchi's practice of Buddhism took his life to an even deeper and broader dimension, resulting in the establishment of the ''\u201d S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai''\u201d (\u5275 \u4fa1 \u6559 \u80b2 \u5b66 \u4f1a;  English: Value-Creation Education Society), a society for educators and teachers, which later became the predecessor of today's [[Soka Gakkai]] organization. \n\nMakiguchi found support for his theory of value-creation and a world view consistent with his aims of educational reform and social betterment centered on addressing the subjective realities of the individual.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Miwa |first=Zeho |date=December 2002 |title=A consideration of how the works of Nichiren were received by readers: the case of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi |journal=Journal of Indian and Buddhist Studies |volume=51 |number=1 |pages=520\u2013524 |doi=10.4259/ibk.51.524 |access-date=12 September 2018|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/51/1/51_1_524/_pdf }}</ref> His close friend and disciple, [[Josei Toda]] followed his Buddhist conversion afterwards in 1930. The ''\u201cZoku Ningen Kakumei\u201d ''(English: Human Revolution), a 1976 film produced by the [[Soka Gakkai]] also re-dramatizes these events.<ref> https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0164237/</ref>\n\n== Wartime arrest ==\nDuring [[World War II]], he opposed Japan's military government's attempts to impose the doctrine of [[State Shinto]] through strict control of religions and thoughts inimical to its war effort. While there was some debate as to whether Makiguchi's actions were in direct opposition to the war,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Miyata|first=Koichi|year=2002|title=Critical Comments on Brian Victoria's \"Engaged Buddhism: A Skeleton in the Closet?\"|url=http://www.globalbuddhism.org/jgb/index.php/jgb/article/view/38/46|url-status=live|journal=Journal of Global Buddhism|volume=3|pages=79\u201385|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801184920/http://www.globalbuddhism.org/jgb/index.php/jgb/article/view/38/46|archivedate=August 1, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Victoria|first=Brian|year=2001|title=Engaged Buddhism: A Skeleton in the Closet?|url=http://www.globalbuddhism.org/2/victoria011.html|url-status=dead||journal=Journal of Global Buddhism|volume=2|pages=72\u201391|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531021739/http://www.globalbuddhism.org/2/victoria011.html|archivedate=May 31, 2013|accessdate=2013-05-31}}</ref> it is clear that \"his outspoken criticism of the prevailing belief system represents an implicit and explicit protest against an extreme [[brainwashing|abuse of the educational process]] for militarist purposes.\"<ref name=Ito2009>{{cite journal |last=Ito |first=Takao |title=Reading Resistance: The Record of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi's Interrogation by Wartime Japan's 'Thought Police' |journal=Educational Studies|volume=45 |issue=2|pages=133\u2013145 |doi=10.1080/00131940902762169}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943, due to his refusal to accept the [[talisman]] and support the war,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmakiguchi.org/religiousreformer/asreligiousreformer/detainmentinterrogation.html|title=Tsunesaburo Makiguchi|author=Tsunesaburo Makiguchi Website Committee|work=Religious Reformer|publisher=Soka Gakkai}}</ref> he was arrested and imprisoned as a \"thought criminal\" together with [[J\u014dsei Toda]] and 20 senior leaders of S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai for violating the [[Peace Preservation Law#Public Security Preservation Law of 1925|Peace Preservation Law]] revised in 1941 and under which tens of thousands were arrested. Already in his seventies, Makiguchi was subjected to harsh interrogation as the authorities sought to force him to recant his beliefs. Most of the other imprisoned members of Soka Kyoiku Gakkai caved to the extreme interrogation tactics, however Makiguchi never yielded, continuing to assert the value of [[freedom of religion]] as a fundamental [[human rights|human right]]. On 18 November 1944, Makiguchi died in prison of malnutrition.<ref>https://www.tmakiguchi.org/biography.html</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nMakiguchi is remembered to this day by members of the Soka Gakkai in Japan and the [[Soka Gakkai International]] (SGI) around the world. During morning and evening prayers, members take a moment to express gratitude to the first three presidents of Soka Gakkai: Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi (president from 1930-1944), J\u014dsei Toda (president from 1951\u20131958), and [[Daisaku Ikeda]] (president from 1960\u20131979, honorary president from 1979 to the present and president of SGI from 1975 to the present).\n\nA secular network of Soka schools around the world, including several independent secondary schools, and two universities ([[S\u014dka University]] of Japan and [[Soka University of America]]) were established by Daisaku Ikeda based on Makiguchi's pedagogy.\n\nMakiguchi's value-creating system of education has attracted the attention of educators around the world. His ''S\u014dka Ky\u014dikugaku Taikei'' has been translated into [[English language|English]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[French language|French]] and [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]. In [[Brazil]], Makiguchi's theory of education based on value-creation has been sponsored in 55 schools and introduced in 1,103 classrooms to more than 340,000 students.<ref>de Melo Silva, Dilma, \"Makiguchi Project in Action\u2014Enhancing Education for Peace,\" The Journal of Oriental Studies, vol. 10 (2000), p62</ref>\n\n==In film==\nA 1976 fictionalised film \u201cZoku Ningen Kakumei\u201d (The Human Revolution), produced by the [[Soka Gakkai]] re-dramatizes the life of Makiguchi, including fictional scenes of encountering [[Nichiren]] during an apparition and going through various difficulties during the [[Second World War]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Books ==\n* ''Education for Creative Living: Ideas and Proposals of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi'', Iowa State University Press, 1989; {{ISBN|978-0813803920}}\n* ''Makiguchi the Value Creator: Revolutionary Japanese Educator and Founder of Soka Gakkai'', Weatherhill, 1994; {{ISBN|978-0834803183}}\n* ''A Geography of Human Life'', Caddo Gap Pr, 2002; {{ISBN|978-1880192429}}\n* ''Makiguchi and Gandhi: Their Education Relevance for the 21st Century'', UPS, 2008; {{ISBN|978-0761840688}}\n* ''Soka Education: For the Happiness of the Individual'', Middleway Press, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0977924554}}\n* ''Tsunesaburo Makiguchi (1871-1944): Educational Philosophy in Context'', Routledge, 2013; {{ISBN|978-0415718776}}\n* ''Philosophy of Value'' by Tsunesaburo Makiguchi, translated by Translation Division Overseas Bureau.  Seikyo Press, Tokyo, 1964.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\nIkeda, Daisaku. \"John Dewey and Tsunesaburo Makiguchi: Confluences of Thought and Action.\" 2001. In ''Soka Education: For the Happiness of the Individual'', 1-32. Santa Monica, CA: Middleway Press, 2010.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://tmakiguchi.org Official Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi website]\n* [http://sgi.org Official Soka Gakkai International website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box| before=new office | title=1st President of [[Soka Gakkai|S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai]] | after=[[J\u014dsei Toda]] | years=18 November 1930 \u2013 18 November 1944}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makiguchi, Tsunesaburo}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Soka Gakkai]]\n[[Category:Members of S\u014dka Gakkai]]\n[[Category:People from Niigata Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Nichiren Buddhists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Human geographers]]\n[[Category:Japanese educational theorists]]\n[[Category:Buddhist martyrs]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=September 2007}}\n{{short description|educator and founding president of Soka Gakkai}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox President\n|name=Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi\n|image=Makiguchi.jpg\n|office=1st President of [[Soka Gakkai|S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai]]\n|term=18 November 1930 - 18 November 1944\n|successor=[[J\u014dsei Toda]] (removed Ky\u014diku from the organization's name)\n|birth_date=23 July 1871 ([[Lunar calendar]] date on 6 June)\n|birth_place=[[Kashiwazaki, Niigata|Kashiwazaki]], [[Niigata Prefecture]], [[Japan]]\n|death_date=18 November 1944 (aged 73)\n|death_place=[[Sugamo Prison]] (present-day Toda Memorial Auditorium{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}), [[Toshima, Tokyo|Toshima]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n|resting_place = [[Taiseki-ji]] Head Temple by Gojunoto Pagoda (left backside), [[Fujinomiya]], [[Shizuoka Prefecture]], Japan<br />{{small|(since 1944\u2013Present)}}\n|alma_mater     = {{plainlist|\n*Sapporo Normal School (present-day [[Hokkaido University of Education]])}}\n}}\n\n{{Buddhism}}\n\n'''Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi''' (\u7267\u53e3 \u5e38\u4e09\u90ce, ''Makiguchi Tsunesabur\u014d'' 23 July 1871<ref>{{cite book|last=Makiguchi|first=Tsunesabur\u014d|date=1989|title=Education for Creative Living|trans-title=Ideas and Proposals of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Education_for_Creative_Living.html?id=AUY4AAAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|language=English|location=Iowa, U.S.|publisher=Iowa State University Press|isbn=0813803918}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://online.verypdf.com/u/71844/api/20150918-030325-5850041233.pdf|title=Significant SGI Dates|work=VeryPDF Software|publisher=VeryPDF Software}}</ref> [Lunar calendar date on 6 June] \u2013 18 November 1944) was a Japanese educator who founded and became the first president of the S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai (Value-Creating Education Society), the predecessor of today's [[Soka Gakkai]].\n\n== Early life and career ==\nMakiguchi was born in the small village of [[Kashiwazaki, Niigata]] Prefecture, Japan, in 23 July 1871 (Lunar calendar date on 6 June). Adopted by the Makiguchi family, he moved to [[Hokkaido]], Japan's northernmost island, at the age of 14. Working his way through school, he graduated from [[Sapporo]] Normal School (today's [[Hokkaido University of Education]]). First employed as an assistant teacher at a primary school affiliated with his alma mater, he later taught high school and served as a dormitory superintendent.\n\nMakiguchi's environmentally-minded new approach to geography appears in his book ''Jinsei Chirigaku'' (A Geography of Human Life) published in 1903 when he was 32. In this work, Makiguchi rejects the prevailing approach to the study of geography, based on the rote memorization of facts and place names, instead advocating a rational understanding of geography based on the relationship of the individual, human activity and industrial advancement to nature. This is one of, if not the, first published example of modern environmentalist thinking.<ref name=Odata1994>{{cite journal |last=Odata |first=Toshihiro |date=1994 |title=\u7267\u53e3\u5e38\u4e09\u90ce \u300e\u4eba\u751f\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u300f \u306e\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u53f2\u4e0a\u306e\u518d\u8a55\u4fa1 |trans-title=A Reappraisal of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi's 'Jinsei Chirigaku' in the History of Geography in Japan |language=Japanese |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_pdf/-char/en |format=pdf |journal=Chiri-Kagaku [Geographical Sciences] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=197\u2013212 |doi=10.20630/chirikagaku.49.4_197 |accessdate=21 August 2018 |layurl=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_article}}</ref>\n\nAlthough recognized as an able teacher, Makiguchi's uncompromising attitude toward authorities created problems. His clashes with officials of the Ministry of Education, school inspectors, ward assemblymen, city councilmen, and top officials of the city of Tokyo were frequent and resulted in frequent transfers between schools.<ref>Murata, Kiyoaki. ''Japan's New Buddhism: An Objective Account of Soka Gakkai.'' New York and Tokyo: Weatherhill, 1969. pp. 73-74</ref> After moving to Tokyo, he served as principal in a succession of six primary schools, from 1913 to 1932.\n\nDuring those years, he devoted much consideration to the relationship between life and education, developing his theories on ''s\u014dka'' or the creation of value, the happiness of the individual, the prosperity of society at large, and their interrelationships in practice.\n\n== Educational reformer ==\nHis aforementioned work ''Jinsei Chirigaku'' (''A Geography of Human Life''), predates the academic study of geography at the [[Imperial Universities]] of Kyoto and Tokyo in 1907 and 1911, respectively, and pioneered a new approach to teaching geography in Japan. Written between the [[First Sino-Japanese War]] and the [[Russo-Japanese War]], the work presents [[human geography]] as a subject for both [[formal learning|formal]] and [[nonformal learning]] to advance an understanding of cultural differences shaping and shaped by the relationship between human activity and its natural environment.<ref name=Odata1994>{{cite journal |last=Odata |first=Toshihiro |date=1994 |title=\u7267\u53e3\u5e38\u4e09\u90ce \u300e\u4eba\u751f\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u300f \u306e\u5730\u7406\u5b66\u53f2\u4e0a\u306e\u518d\u8a55\u4fa1 |trans-title=A Reappraisal of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi's 'Jinsei Chirigaku' in the History of Geography in Japan |language=Japanese |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_pdf/-char/en |format=pdf |journal=Chiri-Kagaku [Geographical Sciences] |volume=49 |issue=4 |pages=197\u2013212 |doi=10.20630/chirikagaku.49.4_197 |accessdate=21 August 2018 |layurl=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/chirikagaku/49/4/49_KJ00003719645/_article}}</ref> While \"Japanese geographers of the time were chiefly concerned with describing the physical features of the earth,\"<ref>Murata, p72</ref> Makiguchi was arguably the first to discuss human geography as a system of knowledge correlating [[location theory]] and [[spatial distribution]] of human phenomena with economic, social and political geographies.<ref name=Takeuchi-Nozawa1988>{{cite journal |last1=Takeuchi |first1=Keiichi |last2=Nozawa |first2=Hideki |title= Recent Trends in Studies on the History of Geographical Thought in Japan\u2014Mainly on the History of Japanese Geographical Thought |url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/grj1984b/61/1/61_1_59/_pdf/-char/en |format=pdf |journal= Geographical Review of Japan |volume=61 (Ser. B) |number=1 |pages=59\u201373 |accessdate=21 August 2018}}</ref>{{rp|64\u201365}} In Makiguchi's words, \"it is through our spiritual interaction with the earth that the characteristics that we think of as human are ignited and nurtured within us.\"<ref>Makiguchi, Tsunesaburo. A Geography of Human Life. Ed. by Dayle M. Bethel. Caddo Gap Press, 2002, p25</ref> In this work, Makiguchi also formulated the concept of humanitarian competition as an approach to international relations, writing that: \"The important thing is the setting of a goal of well being and protection of all people, including oneself but not at the increase of self-interest alone. In other words, the aim is the betterment of others and in doing so, one chooses ways that will yield personal benefit as well as benefits to others. It is a conscious effort to create a more harmonious community life.\"<ref>Makiguchi. A Geography of Human Life. p.286</ref> This publication is one of, if not the, earliest set of ideas in the global modern environmental movement.\n\nIn response to problems throughout the education system that resulted from the Meiji government's adoption of the [[Imperial Rescript]], Makiguchi published the first volume of ''S\u014dka Ky\u014dikugaku Taikei'' (''The System of Value-Creation Pedagogy'') together with his close friend and disciple [[J\u014dsei Toda]] on November 18, 1930.<ref>Kumagaki, Kazunori. \"Value-Creating Pedagogy and Japanese Education in the Modern Era,\" ''The Journal of Oriental Studies, vol. 10 (2000) Special Issue'', p31</ref> The date was later adopted as the Founding Day of S\u014dka Gakkai. The four-volume work, published over a period of five years, sets forth his thoughts on education and proposals for systemic reform. Rather than education serving the state, as embodied in the [[Imperial Rescript on Education]], Makiguchi proposed a student-centered education with the purpose of ensuring the happiness of the learner.<ref>Kumagai, pp32-34</ref>\n\nHe also proposed the creation of an educational system comprising a partnership of school, home and community. In this system, a child would spend half a day in school and the other half in apprenticeships and other types of work activities at home and in the community befitting the nature and needs of the child. Makiguchi felt that implementing such a system would change bored, apathetic learners into eager, self-directed students.\n\n\"Makiguchi developed a theory of value that combined the idea of happiness as the goal of life with that of value as something that can be created. ... In value-creating pedagogy the main point of education is to aim for a happy life and develop the ability and attitude required to create value.\"<ref>Kumagai, p41</ref>\n\n== Conversion to Buddhism==\nIn June 1928, Makiguchi embraced [[Nichiren Buddhism]], having been introduced to Buddhism by his friend Sokei Mitani who was at time working as a [[Meijiro Kenshin Junior and Senior High School|Meijiro high school]] principal in [[Shinjuku, Tokyo]]. In Nichiren Buddhism, Makiguchi discovered a deep resonance with ideas he had been developing throughout his life.<ref>https://www.tmakiguchi.org/biography.html</ref>\n\nMakiguchi's practice of Buddhism took his life to an even deeper and broader dimension, resulting in the establishment of the ''\u201d S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai''\u201d (\u5275 \u4fa1 \u6559 \u80b2 \u5b66 \u4f1a;  English: Value-Creation Education Society), a society for educators and teachers, which later became the predecessor of today's [[Soka Gakkai]] organization. \n\nMakiguchi found support for his theory of value-creation and a world view consistent with his aims of educational reform and social betterment centered on addressing the subjective realities of the individual.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Miwa |first=Zeho |date=December 2002 |title=A consideration of how the works of Nichiren were received by readers: the case of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi |journal=Journal of Indian and Buddhist Studies |volume=51 |number=1 |pages=520\u2013524 |doi=10.4259/ibk.51.524 |access-date=12 September 2018|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/ibk1952/51/1/51_1_524/_pdf }}</ref> His close friend and disciple, [[Josei Toda]] followed his Buddhist conversion afterwards in 1930. The ''\u201cZoku Ningen Kakumei\u201d ''(English: Human Revolution), a 1976 film produced by the [[Soka Gakkai]] also re-dramatizes these events.<ref> https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0164237/</ref>\n\n== Wartime arrest ==\nDuring [[World War II]], he opposed Japan's military government's attempts to impose the doctrine of [[State Shinto]] through strict control of religions and thoughts inimical to its war effort. While there was some debate as to whether Makiguchi's actions were in direct opposition to the war,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Miyata|first=Koichi|year=2002|title=Critical Comments on Brian Victoria's \"Engaged Buddhism: A Skeleton in the Closet?\"|url=http://www.globalbuddhism.org/jgb/index.php/jgb/article/view/38/46|url-status=live|journal=Journal of Global Buddhism|volume=3|pages=79\u201385|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180801184920/http://www.globalbuddhism.org/jgb/index.php/jgb/article/view/38/46|archivedate=August 1, 2018|accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Victoria|first=Brian|year=2001|title=Engaged Buddhism: A Skeleton in the Closet?|url=http://www.globalbuddhism.org/2/victoria011.html|url-status=dead||journal=Journal of Global Buddhism|volume=2|pages=72\u201391|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130531021739/http://www.globalbuddhism.org/2/victoria011.html|archivedate=May 31, 2013|accessdate=2013-05-31}}</ref> it is clear that \"his outspoken criticism of the prevailing belief system represents an implicit and explicit protest against an extreme [[brainwashing|abuse of the educational process]] for militarist purposes.\"<ref name=Ito2009>{{cite journal |last=Ito |first=Takao |title=Reading Resistance: The Record of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi's Interrogation by Wartime Japan's 'Thought Police' |journal=Educational Studies|volume=45 |issue=2|pages=133\u2013145 |doi=10.1080/00131940902762169}}</ref>\n\nIn 1943, due to his refusal to accept the [[talisman]] and support the war,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmakiguchi.org/religiousreformer/asreligiousreformer/detainmentinterrogation.html|title=Tsunesaburo Makiguchi|author=Tsunesaburo Makiguchi Website Committee|work=Religious Reformer|publisher=Soka Gakkai}}</ref> he was arrested and imprisoned as a \"thought criminal\" together with [[J\u014dsei Toda]] and 20 senior leaders of S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai for violating the [[Peace Preservation Law#Public Security Preservation Law of 1925|Peace Preservation Law]] revised in 1941 and under which tens of thousands were arrested. Yet, in spite of being subjected to harsh interrogations, he never retreated from his beliefs; the 72-year-old former principal continued to assert the value of [[freedom of religion]] as a fundamental [[human rights|human right]]. On 18 November 1944, he died in prison of extreme malnutrition. His cremated remains were laid to rest at the left backside of the Five-Story ''Gojunoto'' [[Pagoda]] at [[Taiseki-ji]], the head temple of [[Nichiren Sh\u014dsh\u016b]], where a [[Buddhist Stupa]] memorializes his grave today.<ref>Daniel B. Montgomery: Fire in the Lotus, Mandala 1991, S. 186-187</ref>{{failed verification|date=March 2020}}<ref>http://www.wrs.vcu.edu/profiles/SokaGakkai.htm</ref>{{dead link|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nMakiguchi is remembered to this day by members of the Soka Gakkai in Japan and the [[Soka Gakkai International]] (SGI) around the world. During morning and evening prayers, members take a moment to express gratitude to the first three presidents of Soka Gakkai: Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi (president from 1930-1944), J\u014dsei Toda (president from 1951\u20131958), and [[Daisaku Ikeda]] (president from 1960\u20131979, honorary president from 1979 to the present and president of SGI from 1975 to the present).\n\nA secular network of Soka schools around the world, including several independent secondary schools, and two universities ([[S\u014dka University]] of Japan and [[Soka University of America]]) were established by Daisaku Ikeda based on Makiguchi's pedagogy.\n\nMakiguchi's value-creating system of education has attracted the attention of educators around the world. His ''S\u014dka Ky\u014dikugaku Taikei'' has been translated into [[English language|English]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[French language|French]] and [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]. In [[Brazil]], Makiguchi's theory of education based on value-creation has been sponsored in 55 schools and introduced in 1,103 classrooms to more than 340,000 students.<ref>de Melo Silva, Dilma, \"Makiguchi Project in Action\u2014Enhancing Education for Peace,\" The Journal of Oriental Studies, vol. 10 (2000), p62</ref>\n\n==In film==\nA 1976 fictionalised film \u201cZoku Ningen Kakumei\u201d (The Human Revolution), produced by the [[Soka Gakkai]] re-dramatizes the life of Makiguchi, including fictional scenes of encountering [[Nichiren]] during an apparition and going through various difficulties during the [[Second World War]].{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n== Books ==\n* ''Education for Creative Living: Ideas and Proposals of Tsunesaburo Makiguchi'', Iowa State University Press, 1989; {{ISBN|978-0813803920}}\n* ''Makiguchi the Value Creator: Revolutionary Japanese Educator and Founder of Soka Gakkai'', Weatherhill, 1994; {{ISBN|978-0834803183}}\n* ''A Geography of Human Life'', Caddo Gap Pr, 2002; {{ISBN|978-1880192429}}\n* ''Makiguchi and Gandhi: Their Education Relevance for the 21st Century'', UPS, 2008; {{ISBN|978-0761840688}}\n* ''Soka Education: For the Happiness of the Individual'', Middleway Press, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0977924554}}\n* ''Tsunesaburo Makiguchi (1871-1944): Educational Philosophy in Context'', Routledge, 2013; {{ISBN|978-0415718776}}\n* ''Philosophy of Value'' by Tsunesaburo Makiguchi, translated by Translation Division Overseas Bureau.  Seikyo Press, Tokyo, 1964.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Bibliography ===\nIkeda, Daisaku. \"John Dewey and Tsunesaburo Makiguchi: Confluences of Thought and Action.\" 2001. In ''Soka Education: For the Happiness of the Individual'', 1-32. Santa Monica, CA: Middleway Press, 2010.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://tmakiguchi.org Official Tsunesabur\u014d Makiguchi website]\n* [http://sgi.org Official Soka Gakkai International website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box| before=new office | title=1st President of [[Soka Gakkai|S\u014dka Ky\u014diku Gakkai]] | after=[[J\u014dsei Toda]] | years=18 November 1930 \u2013 18 November 1944}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makiguchi, Tsunesaburo}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Soka Gakkai]]\n[[Category:Members of S\u014dka Gakkai]]\n[[Category:People from Niigata Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Nichiren Buddhists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Human geographers]]\n[[Category:Japanese educational theorists]]\n[[Category:Buddhist martyrs]]\n", "name_user": "Nihonjimu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fuller description from bio", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tsunesabur%C5%8D_Makiguchi"}
{"title_page": "Amran Al-Hidi", "text_new": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Amran Al-Hidi\n| image = \n| fullname = Amran Said Juma Kharbash Al-Hidi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/players/amran-said-juma-kharbash-al-hidi/630260/|title=Oman - Amran Said Al Hidi - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway|website=us.soccerway.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/amran-al-hidi/|title=Amran Al Hidi|website=worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1998|04|07|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/amran-al-hidi/|title=Amran Al Hidi|website=worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Saham]], Oman\n| height = \n| position = Midfielder<br>Defender\n| currentclub = [[Suwaiq Club]]\n| clubnumber = \n| years1 = \n| clubs1 = \n| years2 = \n| clubs2 = \n| nationalyears1 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Oman national football team|Oman]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate = 2 April 2020\n}}\n\n'''Amran Said Juma Kharbash Al-Hidi''' (born 7 April 1998) is an Omani [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Suwaiq Club]] and the [[Oman national football team|Omani national team]].\n\nHe debuted internationally on 5 September 2019, during the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] match in a 1\u20132 victory against [[India national football team|India]].\n\nOn 14 November 2019, Al-Hidi scored his first goal in a major competition for Oman against [[Bangladesh national football team|Bangladesh]] in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/asia/matches/match/400080695/|title=FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022\u2122 Qualifiers - Asia - Matches - Oman - Bangladesh - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT|75525}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Omani footballers]]\n[[Category:Oman international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Al-Suwaiq Club players]]\n[[Category:Oman Professional League players]]\n[[Category:People from Al Batinah North Governorate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Amran Al-Hidi\n| image = \n| fullname = Amran Said Juma Kharbash Al-Hidi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/players/amran-said-juma-kharbash-al-hidi/630260/|title=Oman - Amran Said Al Hidi - Profile with news, career statistics and history - Soccerway|website=us.soccerway.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/amran-al-hidi/|title=Amran Al Hidi|website=worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1998|04|07|df=y}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldfootball.net/player_summary/amran-al-hidi/|title=Amran Al Hidi|website=worldfootball.net|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Saham]], Oman\n| height = \n| position = Midfielder<br>Defender\n| currentclub = [[Suwaiq Club]]\n| clubnumber = \n| years1 = \n| clubs1 = \n| years2 = \n| clubs2 = \n| nationalyears1 = 2019\u2013\n| nationalteam1 = [[Oman national football team|Oman]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 8\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| pcupdate = \n| ntupdate = 2 April 2020\n}}\n\n'''Amran Said Juma Kharbash Al-Hidi''' (born 7 April 1998) is a Omani [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[Suwaiq Club]] and the [[Oman national football team|Omani national team]].\n\nHe debuted internationally on 5 September 2019, during the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] match in a 1-2 victory against [[India national football team|India]].\n\nOn 14 November 2019, Al-Hidi scored his first goal in a major competition for Oman against [[Bangladesh national football team|Bangladesh]] in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/asia/matches/match/400080695/|title=FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022\u2122 Qualifiers - Asia - Matches - Oman - Bangladesh - FIFA.com|last=FIFA.com|website=www.fifa.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{NFT|75525}}\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Omani footballers]]\n[[Category:Oman international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Al-Suwaiq Club players]]\n[[Category:Oman Professional League players]]\n[[Category:People from Al Batinah North Governorate]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1-2 \u2192 1\u20132, a Omani \u2192 an Omani", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amran_Al-Hidi"}
